'''Anila''' or '''Anil''' ([[Sanskrit]]: अनिल ''{{IAST|anila}}'' "wind") is one of the [[Vasu]]s in [[Hinduism]], gods of the elements of the cosmos. He is equated with the wind god [[Vayu|Vāyu]], ''Anil'' being understood as the name normally used for Vāyu when numbered among the Vasus.<ref>Gaṅgā Rām Garg -''Encyclopaedia of the Hindu World'' 1992 - Page 479 " '''Anila''' [1] See Anila Vatyayana. '''Anila''' [2] Synonym of Visnu (Mb. Anu. 149.38). '''Anila''' [3] Synonym of Siva (Mb. Anu. 149.100). '''Anila''' [4] The god of wind: Vayu (q.v.). '''Anila''' [5] The 'immortal air', to which at death mortal breath returns, as the body burns to ..... '''Anila''' [7] Fifth of the Asta (8) Vasus. His father was Dharma and mother Svasa. Anila's wife was Siva, by whom he had two sons: Manojava and Avijnanagati ... 1.15.110-15). He attended Skanda's investiture. See Vasu."</ref>

