'''Agni''' ({{lang-sa|अग्नि|translit=Agni}}, {{IPA-sa|ˈɐgnɪ}}) is a Sanskrit word meaning fire and connotes the [[Vedas|Vedic]] fire deity of [[Hinduism]].<ref name="Olivelle1998p18">{{cite book |first=Patrick |last=Olivelle |author-link=Patrick Olivelle|title=The Early Upanishads: Annotated Text and Translation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lsp18ZvstrcC |year=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-535242-9|page=18}}</ref><ref name="Lochtefeld2002p14">{{cite book |first=James G. |last=Lochtefeld |year=2002 |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of sanatan dharm (Hinduism) |volume=A-M |pages=[https://archive.org/details/illustratedencyc0000loch/page/n439 14]–15 |publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group |isbn=978-0-8239-3179-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/illustratedencyc0000loch |url-access=registration}}</ref><ref name=jamison2014p40>{{cite book |first1=Stephanie W. |last1=Jamison |author1-link=Stephanie W. Jamison  |first2=Joel P. |last2=Brereton |year=2014 |title=The Rigveda: 3-Volume Set |pages=40–41 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-972078-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fgzVAwAAQBAJ}}</ref> He is also the [[Guardians of the directions#Aṣṭa-Dikpāla ("Guardians of Eight Directions")|guardian deity of the southeast direction]] and is typically found in southeast corners of [[Hindu temple]]s.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Stella |last1=Kramrisch |first2=Raymond |last2=Burnier |title=The Hindu Temple |year=1976 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0223-0 |page=92 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NNcXrBlI9S0C&pg=PA92}}</ref> In the [[Hindu cosmology|classical cosmology]] of the Indian religions, Agni as fire is one of the five inert impermanent elements (''[[Pancha Bhoota|pañcabhūtá]]'') along with space (''ākāśa''), water (''ap''), air (''vāyu'') and earth (''pṛthvī''), the five combining to form the empirically perceived material existence (''Prakṛti'').<ref name="Lochtefeld2002p14"/><ref>{{cite book |first=Alexander |last=Wynne |title=The Origin of Buddhist Meditation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ElIupyX_SYAC |year=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-09741-8|pages=31–32}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Kapila |last=Vatsyayan |title=Prakr̥ti: Vedic, Buddhist, and Jain traditions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jKLpAAAAMAAJ|year=1995|publisher=Indira Gandhi National Centre for the Arts|isbn=978-81-246-0038-2|pages=7, 94–95}}</ref>

In Vedic literature, Agni is a major and oft-invoked god along with [[Indra]] and [[Soma (deity)|Soma]].<ref name="Lochtefeld2002p14"/><ref>[[Richard Cavendish (occult writer)|Cavendish, Richard]] (1998). ''Mythology, An Illustrated Encyclopedia of the Principal Myths and Religions of the World''. {{ISBN|1-84056-070-3}}</ref> Agni is considered the mouth of the gods and goddesses and the medium that conveys offerings to them in a ''[[homa (ritual)|homa]]'' (votive ritual).<ref name="Olivelle1998p18"/><ref name=richardpayne2>{{cite book |first=Richard |last=Payne |year=2015 |title=Homa Variations: The study of ritual change across the longue durée |pages=1–3 |editor-first=Michael |editor-last=Witzel|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-935158-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tIShCgAAQBAJ }}</ref><ref name=axelmichaels237>{{cite book |first=Axel |last=Michaels |year=2016 |title=Homo Ritualis: Hindu hitual and its significance for ritual theory |pages=237–248 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-026263-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DSaxCgAAQBAJ}}</ref> He is conceptualized in ancient Hindu texts to exist at three levels, on earth as fire, in the atmosphere as lightning, and in the sky as the sun. This triple presence accords him as the messenger between the deities and human beings in the Vedic scriptures.<ref name="Lochtefeld2002p14"/> The relative importance of Agni declined in the post-Vedic era,<ref name=williams49/> as he was internalised<ref name="Witzel2015p79">{{cite book |first=Tadeusz |last=Skorupski |editor-first=Michael |year=2015 |editor-last=Witzel |title=Homa Variations: The study of ritual change across the longue durée |pages=78–84 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-935158-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tIShCgAAQBAJ}}</ref> and his identity evolved to metaphorically represent all transformative energy and knowledge in the [[Upanishads]] and later Hindu literature.<ref name=shende1/><ref name="Hopkins1968p98"/><ref name=baumer203/> Agni remains an integral part of Hindu traditions, such as being the central witness of the rite-of-passage ritual in traditional [[Hindu wedding]]s called ''Saptapadi'' or ''Agnipradakṣiṇam'' (seven steps and mutual vows), in the [[Upanayana]] ceremony of rite of passage, as well being part of the ''diyā'' (lamp) in festivals such as [[Diwali|Deepavali]] and ''Aarti'' in [[Puja (Hinduism)|Puja]].<ref name="Lochtefeld2002p14"/>

Agni (Pali: ''Aggi'') is a term that appears extensively in Buddhist texts<ref>{{cite book |first1=T.W. Rhys |last1=Davids |first2=William |last2=Stede |year=1905 |title=The Pali-English Dictionary |pages=4–5 |publisher=Asian Educational Services |isbn=978-81-206-1273-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dHWHmHnMLtAC}}</ref> and in the literature related to the Senika heresy debate within the Buddhist traditions.<ref name=buswelllopez852>{{cite book | first1=Robert E. Jr. |last1=Buswell | first2=Donald S. Jr. |last2=Lopez |year=2013 |title=The Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism |pages=852, 962 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=978-1-4008-4805-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DXN2AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA852}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first1=Masao |last1=Abe |first2=Steven |last2=Heine |year=1992 |title=A Study of Dogen: His philosophy and religion |pages=158–162 |publisher=State University of New York Press |isbn=978-0-7914-0837-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dx300N5VQAIC&pg=PA158}}</ref> In the ancient [[Jainism]] thought, Agni (fire) contains soul and fire-bodied beings,<ref name="Christopher 2006">{{cite book |first=Christopher Key |last=Chapple |year=2006 |title=Jainism and Ecology: Nonviolence in the Web of Life |pages=31, 43–44, 56, 173–175 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-2045-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=abLZNdYxay8C}}</ref> additionally appears as ''Agni-kumara'' or "fire princes" in its theory of rebirth and a class of reincarnated beings<ref name="Helmuth 1999">{{cite book |first=Helmuth |last=von&nbsp;Glasenapp |year=1999 |title=Jainism: An Indian Religion of Salvation |pages=263–264 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1376-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WzEzXDk0v6sC}}</ref> and is discussed in its texts with the equivalent term '''Tejas'''.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Bettina |last1=Bäumer |first2=Kapila |last2=Vatsyayan |title=Kalatattvakosa: A Lexicon of Fundamental Concepts of the Indian Arts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uPoIZaGGtiMC&pg=PA226 |year=1988|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1402-8|pages=226–227}}</ref>

==Etymology, meaning and other names==
[[File:(A) Hindu puja, yajna, yagna, Havanam in progress.jpg|thumb|upright|Agni (fire) is a part of major [[Sanskara (rite of passage)|rites-of-passage]] rituals such as weddings and cremation in Indian religions.]]

Sanskrit [[wikt:अग्नि|अग्नि (''Agni'')]] continues one of two core terms for fire reconstructed to [[Proto-Indo-European]], ''[[wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Indo-European/h₁n̥gʷnís|*h₁n̥gʷnís]]'', other reflexes of which include '''''*En''''' or ''*'''Enji''''' ({{IPA-sq|ɛɲi|}}) is the reconstructed name of the [[fire]] [[fire god|god]] in the [[Albanian mythology|Albanian pagan mythology]], which continues to be used in the modern [[Albanian language]] to refer to [[Thursday]] (''e enjte''){{sfn|Tagliavini|1963|p=103}}{{sfn|Orel|1998|p=88}}{{sfn|Lurker|2005|p=57}} 
[[Latin]] ''[[wikt:ignis|ignis]]'' (the root of English ''ignite''), Lithuanian ''[[wikt:ugnis|ugnis]]'', Kurdish agir, Old Slavonian [[wikt:огнь|огнь]] (''ognĭ'')<ref>{{cite book |first=Maurice |last=Phillips |year=1895 |title=The Teaching of the Vedas: What light does it throw on the origin and development of religion? |page=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.205078/page/n64 57] |publisher=Longmans Green |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.205078}}</ref> and its descendants: Russian [[wikt:огонь|огонь]] (''ogon'''), Serbian oganj, Polish ''[[wikt:ogień|ogień]]'', etc., all meaning "fire".<ref>{{cite book |first=Jaan |last=Puhvel |year=2011 |title=Words Beginning with PA |pages=25–26 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |isbn=978-3-11-023865-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4bNY4RoVrawC&pg=PA25}}</ref> 

The [[Vyākaraṇa|ancient Indian grammarians]] variously derived it:
*from root ''aj'', which in Sanskrit means "to drive" in the sense of "nimble, agile";<ref>{{cite book |first=Arthur Anthony |last=MacDonell |year=1898 |title=Vedic Mythology |page=99 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1113-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b7Meabtj8mcC}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Hervey De Witt |last=Griswold |title=The Religion of the Ṛigveda|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vhkt5K1fw2wC |year=1971|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0745-7|pages=160 footnote 2}}</ref> 
*from ''agri'', the root of which means "first", referring to "that first in the universe to arise" or "fire" according to ''[[Shatapatha Brahmana]]'' section 6.1.1; the Brahmana claims this is cryptically called as Agni because everyone including the gods are known to love short nicknames;<ref>{{cite book|author1=Annette Wilke|author2=Oliver Moebus|title=Sound and Communication: An Aesthetic Cultural History of Sanskrit Hinduism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9wmYz_OtZ_gC |year=2011|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-024003-0|pages=418 with footnote 147}}</ref>
*according to the 5th-century BCE Sanskrit text ''[[Nirukta|Nirukta-Nighantu]]'' in section 7.14, sage Śakapūṇi states the word Agni is derived from three verbs – from 'going', from 'shining or burning', and from 'leading'; the letter "a" (अ) is from root "i" which he claims implies 'to go', the letter "g" (ग्) is from the root "añj" meaning 'to shine' or "dah" meaning 'to burn', and the last letter is by itself the root "nī" (नी) which means 'to lead'.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Nighantu and the Nirukta| author=Lakshman Sarup| year=1998| isbn=978-81-208-1381-6| publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|page=120|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=0l2UOabkPTIC&pg=PA238 }}</ref> None of the three explanations cited above is plausible in the modern scientific sense.

In the early Vedic literature, Agni primarily connotes the fire as a god, one reflecting the primordial powers to consume, transform and convey.<ref name="Macdonell1898p15">{{cite book |first=Arthur Anthony |last=MacDonell |year=1898 |title=Vedic Mythology |pages=15–16, 92–93 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1113-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b7Meabtj8mcC}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=William Norman Brown |author2=Rosane Rocher |year=1978 |title=India and Indology: Selected articles |pages=59–61 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BdaXdGm8h9gC}}</ref> Yet the term is also used with the meaning of a ''Mahabhuta'' (constitutive substance), one of five that the earliest Vedic thinkers believed to constitute material existence, and that later Vedic thinkers such as [[Kanada (philosopher)|Kanada]] and [[Kapila]] expanded widely, namely Akasha (ether, space), Vayu (air), Ap (water), Prithvi (earth) and Agni (fire).<ref name=agrawala28>V.S. Agrawala (1960), [https://www.jstor.org/stable/29754201 Fire in the Ṛigveda], East and West, Volume 11, Number 1 (March 1960), pages 28–32</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Surendranath |last=Dasgupta |title=A History of Indian Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oc0lt2qklycC&pg=PA73|year=1933|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-04779-1|pages=73–76}}</ref>

The word Agni is used in many contexts, ranging from fire in the stomach, the cooking fire in a home, the sacrificial fire in an altar, the fire of cremation, the fire of rebirth, the fire in the energetic saps concealed within plants, the atmospheric fire in lightning and the celestial fire in the sun.<ref name=jamison2014p40/><ref name="Macdonell1898p15"/><ref>{{Cite dictionary|title=अग्नि|date=1899|encyclopedia=A Sanskrit—English Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zUezTfym7CAC&pg=PA5|editor-last=Monier-Williams|editor-first=Sir Monier|publisher=Montilal Banarsidass Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=9788120831056|via=Google Books|type=Reprint (2005)}}</ref> In the [[Brahmana]]s layer of the Vedas, such as in section 5.2.3 of Shatapatha Brahmana, Agni represents all the gods, all concepts of spiritual energy that permeates everything in the universe.<ref name=shende1>N. J. Shende (1965), [https://www.jstor.org/stable/41694176 Agni in the Brahmanas of the Ṛgveda], Annals of the Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Volume 46, Number 1/4, pages 1–28</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Jan |last=Gonda |author-link=Jan Gonda |year=1980 |title=Handbuch Der Orientalistik: Indien. Zweite Abteilung |pages=301–302 |chapter=Deities and their position and function |publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=978-90-04-06210-8 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7UBxYpXWP30C}}</ref> In the Upanishads and post-Vedic literature, Agni additionally became a metaphor for immortal principle in man, and any energy or knowledge that consumes and dispels a state of darkness, transforms and procreates an enlightened state of existence.<ref name="Hopkins1968p98">{{cite book |first=Edward Washburn |last=Hopkins |year=1968 |title=Epic Mythology |pages=97–99 |publisher=Biblo & Tannen |isbn=978-0-8196-0228-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-H0eiuvcG5IC&pg=PA98}}</ref><ref name=baumer203>{{cite book|author1=Bettina Bäumer|author2=Kapila Vatsyayan|title=Kalatattvakosa: A Lexicon of Fundamental Concepts of the Indian Arts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uPoIZaGGtiMC |year=1988|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1402-8|pages=203–204}}</ref><ref name=agrawala28/>

Agni is also famously known as:<ref>Mahabharata Sabha Parva Digvijaya Parva XXXI, prayer of Sahadeva</ref>
* '''Pāvaka''' – sanctifier of everything;
* '''Havyavāhana''' – one who carries the sacrificial butter;
* '''Saptajihvi''' – one with seven tongues (flames); consumes the sacrificial butter very fast;
* '''Vahni''' – travelling with wind;
* '''Anala''' – as one of the Vasus;
* '''Hutāśana''';
* '''Chitrabhānu''' – colourful light;
* '''Jvalana''' – glowing;
* ''' Vaiśvānara''';
* '''Vibhāvasu''' – whose light is wealth.

Other names include Śikhī, Pingesa, Plavanga, Bhūritejaḥ, Rudragarva and Hiraṇyakṛt.

==Origins==
{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=400|caption_align=center
| align    = right
| direction =horizontal
| header=Agnipani (100 BCE)
| image1   = Agnipani statue, Mathura, 100 BCE, Mathura Museum.jpg
| caption1 = Front
| image2   = Agnipani aureole, rear view.jpg
| caption2 = Back of head with flame tongues
| footer="[[Agnipani]]" ("Fire-holder"), 100&nbsp;BCE. Behind its turban, the statue has a flame-shaped aureole incised with flame tongues. [[Mathura Museum]], GMM 87.146
}}
There are many theories about the origins of the god Agni, some tracing it to Indo-European mythologies, others tracing to mythologies within the Indian tradition.<ref name="Bodewitz1976p14">{{cite book |first=H. W. |last=Bodewitz |year=1976 |title=The Daily Evening and Morning Offering (Agnihotra) According to the Brāhmanas |pages=14–19 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1951-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8hmmCoxGmX4C}}</ref><ref name=oflaherty97>{{cite book |first=Wendy Doniger |last=O'Flaherty |year=1994 |title=Hindu Myths |pages=97–98 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=978-0-14-400011-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ajLoN2yuZbwC&pg=PA97}}</ref>

The origin myth found in many Indo-European cultures is one of a bird, or bird like being, that carries or brings fire from the gods to mankind. Alternatively, this messenger brings an elixir of immortality from heaven to earth. In either case, the bird returns everyday with sacrificial offerings for the gods, but sometimes the bird hides or disappears without trace. Agni is molded in similar mythical themes, in some hymns with the phrase the "heavenly bird that flies".<ref name=oflaherty97/><ref name="Doniger1981p80">{{cite book |first=Wendy |last=Doniger |year=1981 |title=The Rig Veda: An Anthology: One Hundred and Eight Hymns, Selected, Translated and Annotated |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=978-0-14-044402-5 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/rigvedapenguincl00anon/page/80 80], 97 |url=https://archive.org/details/rigvedapenguincl00anon |url-access=registration}}</ref>

The earliest layers of the Vedic texts of Hinduism, such as section 6.1 of ''Kaṭhaka Saṃhitā'' and section 1.8.1 of ''Maitrāyaṇī Saṃhitā'' state that the universe began with nothing, neither night nor day existed, what existed was just Prajāpati (also referred to as Brahman).<ref name="Bodewitz1976p14"/> Agni originated from the forehead of [[Prajapati|Prajāpati]], assert these texts. With the creation of Agni came light, and with that were created day and night. Agni, state these ''[[Saṃhitā]]''s, is the same as the [[Brahman]], the truth, the eye of the manifested universe.<ref name="Bodewitz1976p14"/> These mythologies develop into more complex stories about Agni's origins in the later layers of Vedic texts, such as in section 2.1.2 of the ''Taittiriya Brahmana'' and sections 2.2.3–4 of ''Shatapatha Brahmana''.<ref name="Bodewitz1976p14"/>

Agni is originally conceptualized as the ultimate source of the "creator-maintainer-destroyer" triad, then one of the trinities, as the one who ruled the earth. His twin brother [[Indra]] ruled the atmosphere as the god of storm, rain and war, while [[Surya|Sūrya]] ruled the sky and heavens.<ref name=williams49>{{cite book |first=George M. |last=Williams |year=2008 |title=Handbook of Hindu Mythology |pages=48–51 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-533261-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N7LOZfwCDpEC}}</ref>{{efn|The Vedic idea that the sun, lightning, and fire were different manifestation of the same element and principle is summarized in many Hindu texts, such as the ancient ''[[Bṛhaddevatā]]''.<ref name=bettina225>{{cite book |first1=Bettina |last1=Bäumer |first2=Kapila |last2=Vatsyayan |title=Kalatattvakosa: A Lexicon of Fundamental Concepts of the Indian Arts |year=1988 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1402-8 |pages=225–226 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uPoIZaGGtiMC}}</ref>}} His position and importance evolves over time, in the "creator-maintainer-destroyer" aspects of existence in Hindu thought.<ref name="Daniélou1991p106">{{cite book |first=Alain |last=Daniélou |title=The Myths and Gods of India: The Classic Work on Hindu Polytheism from the Princeton Bollingen Series |year=1991 |publisher=Inner Traditions |isbn=978-0-89281-354-4 |pages=106–107 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1HMXN9h6WX0C&pg=PA106}}</ref>{{efn|The Trimurti idea of Hinduism, states [[Jan Gonda]], "seems to have developed from ancient cosmological and ritualistic speculations about the triple character of an individual god, in the first place of '''Agni''', whose births are three or threefold, and who is threefold light, has three bodies and three stations".<ref name=Gonda1969>{{cite journal |first=Jan |last=Gonda |year=1969 |title=The Hindu Trinity |journal=Anthropos |volume=Bd 63/64 |issue=H 1/2 |pages=212–226 |jstor=40457085 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/40457085}}</ref>{{rp||pages=218–219}} Other trinities, beyond the more common "Brahma, Vishnu, Shiva", mentioned in ancient and medieval Hindu texts include: "Indra, Vishnu, Brahmanaspati"; "Agni, Indra, Surya"; "Agni, Vayu, Aditya"; "Mahalakshmi, Mahasarasvati, and Mahakali"; and others.<ref name=Gonda1969/>{{rp|pages=212–226}}<ref name=davidwhite29>{{cite book |first=David |last=White |year=2006 |title=Kiss of the Yogini |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=978-0-226-89484-3 |pages=4, 29}}</ref>}}

The [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] mentions there have been three previous Agnis and current one is the fourth in the series.<ref>{{cite web |title=Satapatha Brahmana Part&nbsp;1 (SBE12) |quote=First Kâ''n''''d''a: I, 2, 3. Third Brâhma''n''a |website=sacred-texts.com |url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/sbr/sbe12/sbe1209.htm}}</ref>

:''Fourfold, namely, was Agni (fire) at first. Now that Agni whom they at first chose for the office of Hotri priest passed away. He also whom they chose the second time passed away. He also whom they chose the third time passed away. Thereupon the one who still constitutes the fire in our own time, concealed himself from fear. He entered into the waters. Him the gods discovered and brought forcibly away from the waters.'' – 1:2:3:1

==Texts==
===Vedas===
[[File:Agni - Kushan Period - ACCN 40-2880 - Government Museum - Mathura 2013-02-23 5714.JPG|thumb|upright|A pre-3rd century CE, [[Kushan Empire]] era red-stone Agni statue. [[Art of Mathura]].]]
In the Vedic pantheon, Agni occupies, after Indra, the most important position.<ref name=jamison2014p40/> Agni is prominent in the hymns of the [[Vedas]] and particularly the [[Brahmanas]]. In the ''[[Rigveda|ṚgVeda]]'' there are over 200 hymns that praise Agni. His name or synonyms appear in nearly a third of 1,028&nbsp;hymns in the ''ṚgVeda''.<ref name="Fowler1999p6"/> The ''ṚgVeda'' opens with a hymn inviting Agni, who is then addressed later in the hymn as the guardian of [[Ṛta]] ([[Dharma]]).<ref>{{cite book |first=Wendy |last=Doniger |year=1988 |title=Textual Sources for the Study of Hinduism |pages=6–7 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-1866-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6hwNAQAAIAAJ}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=William K. |last=Mahony |title=The Artful Universe: An Introduction to the Vedic Religious Imagination |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gNm0NSpNABYC |year=1998|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-3580-9|page=123 verse 8}}</ref>{{efn|Other hymns of the ''Rigveda'' link Ṛta (cosmic harmony) to other Vedic deities, such as verse 10.133.6 calls on Indra for guidance on Ṛta.<ref>{{cite book |first=William K. |last=Mahony |year=1998 |title=The Artful Universe: An Introduction to the Vedic Religious Imagination |pages=46–55 |publisher=State University of New York Press |isbn=978-0-7914-3580-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gNm0NSpNABYC}}</ref>}}

The Vedas describe the parents of Agni as two kindling fire sticks, whose loving action creates him. Just born, he is poetically presented as a tender baby, who needs loving attention lest he vanishes. With care, he sparks and smokes, then flames and grows stronger than his parents, finally so strong that he devours what created him.<ref name="jamison41">{{cite book |author1=Stephanie W. Jamison |author2=Joel P. Brereton |title=The Rigveda: 3-Volume Set |year=2014 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-972078-1 |pages=41–42 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fgzVAwAAQBAJ}}</ref>

The hymns in these ancient texts refer to Agni with numerous epithets and synonyms, such as ''Jātavedas'' (he who knows all generations), ''Vaiśvānara'' (relating to all men), ''Tanūnapāt'' (son of himself, self-made), ''Narāśaṃsa'' (who embodies men's praise), ''Tripatsya'' (with three dwellings), and many others.<ref name="jamison41"/><ref>{{cite book |first=Arthur Anthony |last=MacDonell |year=1898 |title=Vedic Mythology |pages=71, 93–95, 99–100 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1113-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b7Meabtj8mcC}}</ref> In Vedic mythologies, Agni is also presented as one who is mysterious with a tendency to play hide and seek, not just with humans but with the gods. He hides in strange places such as waters where in one myth he imbues life force into living beings that dwell therein, and in another where the fishes report his presence to the gods.<ref>{{cite book |first=Wendy Doniger |last=O'Flaherty |title=Hindu Myths |year=1994 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=978-0-14-400011-1 |pages=97–101 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ajLoN2yuZbwC&pg=PA97}}</ref>

Agni is in hymn 10.124 of the ''ṚgVeda'', a [[Rishi]] (sage-poet-composer) and along with Indra and Sūrya makes up the Vedic triad of deities.<ref>{{cite book|title=Encyclopaedia of the Hindu World Vol.1|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|page=210|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=w9pmo51lRnYC&pg=PA213 |isbn=9788170223740|year=1992}}</ref>

Agni is considered equivalent to and [[henotheism|henotheistically]] identified with all the gods in the Vedic thought, which formed the foundation for the various non-dualistic and monistic theologies of Hinduism.<ref name="Fowler1999p6">{{cite book |first=Merv |last=Fowler |year=1999 |title=Buddhism: Beliefs and practices |pages=6–7 |publisher=Sussex Academic Press |isbn=978-1-898723-66-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A7UKjtA0QDwC&pg=PA6}}</ref> These theme of equivalence is repeatedly presented in the Vedas, such as with the following words in the Maṇḍala 1 of the ''ṚgVeda'':
<blockquote style="background-color:none;margin-right:5em;margin-left:5em;border-left:solid 6px #FFE0BB;padding:1.0em">
<poem>
They call it Indra, Mitra, Varuna, '''Agni''',
and he is heavenly-winged Garutman.
To what is One, sages give many a title,
they call it '''Agni''', Yama, Matarisvan.
</poem>
&nbsp; — ''[[Rigveda|ṚgVeda]] 1.164.46'', Translator: [[Klaus Klostermaier]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Klaus K. |last=Klostermaier |title=A Survey of Hinduism: Third Edition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8CVviRghVtIC |year=2010|publisher=State University of New York Press |isbn=978-0-7914-8011-3|pages=103 with footnote 10 on page 529}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Wendy |last=Doniger |title=The Rig Veda: An Anthology : One Hundred and Eight Hymns, Selected, Translated and Annotated|url=https://archive.org/details/rigvedapenguincl00anon |url-access=registration|year=1981|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=978-0-14-044402-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/rigvedapenguincl00anon/page/80 80]}}</ref><ref>Sanskrit: इन्द्रं मित्रं वरुणमग्निमाहुरथो दिव्यः स सुपर्णो गरुत्मान् । एकं सद्विप्रा बहुधा वदन्त्यग्निं यमं मातरिश्वानमाहुः ॥४६॥, [https://sa.wikisource.org/wiki/ऋग्वेद:_सूक्तं_१.१६४ ऋग्वेद: सूक्तं १.१६४], Wikisource</ref>
</blockquote>

===Upanishads===
[[File:Guardians of the eight directions 03.JPG|thumb|upright|Agni with an aura of flames, seated on ram.]]
Agni features prominently in the major and minor Upanishads of Hinduism. Among the earliest mention is the legend of a boy named [[Satyakāma Jābāla]], of uncertain parentage from an unwed mother, in chapter 4 of the ''[[Chandogya Upanishad|Chhāndogya Upanishad]]'' (~700 BCE). He honestly admits his poverty and that his mother does not know who his father was, an honesty that earns him a spot in a Vedic school (''gurukul'').<ref name=pauldeussen44/><ref name=maxmuller44>Max Muller, [https://archive.org/stream/upanishads01ml#page/60/mode/2up Chandogya Upanishad 4.4 – 4.9], The Upanishads, Part I, [[Oxford University Press]], pages 60–64 with footnotes</ref> During his studies, the boy meets Agni, who then becomes the metaphor for him as a cardinal direction, world body, eye and knowledge, and the abstract principle of Brahman which the Upanishad states is in everything and is everywhere.<ref name=pauldeussen44>Paul Deussen, Sixty Upanishads of the Veda, Volume 1, Motilal Banarsidass, {{ISBN|978-81-208-1468-4}}, pages 122–126 with preface and footnotes</ref><ref name=hume44>Robert Hume, [https://archive.org/stream/thirteenprincipa028442mbp#page/n235/mode/2up Chandogya Upanishad] 4.4 – 4.9, The Thirteen Principal Upanishads, Oxford University Press, pages 218–221</ref><ref name=gjha44>[https://archive.org/stream/Shankara.Bhashya-Chandogya.Upanishad-Ganganath.Jha.1942.English#page/n203/mode/2up Chandogya Upanishad with Shankara Bhashya] Ganganath Jha (Translator), pages 189–198</ref> Agni appears in section 1.13 of ''Chandogya Upanishad'' as well.<ref>Robert Hume, Chandogya Upanishad 1.13.1 – 1.13.4, The Thirteen Principal Upanishads, Oxford University Press, pages 189–190</ref>

In verse 18 of the ''[[Isha Upanishad]]'', Agni is invoked with, "O Agni, you know all the paths, lead me on to success by the good path, keep me away from the wrong path of sin".<ref>{{cite book |translator=Muller, Max |title=Vajasaneyi Samhita (Isha) Upanishad |pages=313–314 |publisher=Oxford University Press |url=https://archive.org/stream/upanishads01ml#page/312/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Paul |last=Deussen |title=Sixty Upaniṣads of the Veda |volume=Part&nbsp;2 |page=551 |year=1990 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-0430-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ghISwAACAAJ}}</ref>{{efn|This prayer to Agni appears in ''Rigveda'' verse 1.89.1, composed before 1200&nbsp;BCE.<ref>E. Washburn Hopkins (1908), [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1507223 The Mediatorial Office of the Vedic Fire-God], The Harvard Theological Review, Cambridge University Press, Volume 1, Number 4, page 509</ref>}} In sections 4.5–6 of the ''[[Maitri Upanishad]]'', students ask their Vedic [[Guru]] (teacher) about which god is best among gods they name, a list that includes Agni.<ref name=cowell45>[https://www.shemtaia.com/SKT/PDF/Upanishads/cowellmaitriskt.pdf Maitri Upanishad – Sanskrit Text with English Translation]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} EB Cowell (Translator), Cambridge University, Bibliotheca Indica, page 254</ref><ref name=hume45>{{citation|first=Robert Ernest|last=Hume|url=https://archive.org/stream/thirteenprincipa028442mbp#page/n443/mode/2up|title=The Thirteen Principal Upanishads|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1921|page=422}}</ref> The Guru replies that they are all supreme, all merely forms of the Brahman, the whole world is Brahman. So pick anyone, suggests the Upanishad, meditate and adore that one, then meditate over them all, then deny and discard the individuality of every one of these gods including of Agni, thus journey unto the universal, for a communion with the [[Purusha]], the [[Atman (Hinduism)|Ātman]].<ref name=maxmuller45>{{cite book |first=Max |last=Muller |title=The Upanishads |volume=Part&nbsp;2 |page=302 |chapter=Maitrayana-Brahmana Upanishad |publisher=Oxford University Press |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/upanishads02ml#page/302/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Paul |last=Deussen |year=1980 |title=Sixty Upaniṣads of the Veda |volume=Part&nbsp;1 |pages=343–344 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1468-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8mSpQo9q-tIC}}</ref>

Sections 3 and 4 of ''[[Kena Upanishad]]'', another major ancient Upanishad, present an allegorical story which includes gods Agni, [[Vayu|Vāyu]], Indra and goddess [[Parvati|Umā]].<ref name=pauldeussen34/> After a battle between good gods and evil demons, where Brahman helps the good gain victory, the gods wonder, "what is this Brahman, a wonderful being?" Agni goes first to find out, but fails. Vāyu too fails.<ref name=pauldeussen34/> Then Indra tries, but meets the goddess who already understands Brahman, explains what Brahman is and how the good reached victory through the nature of Brahman.<ref name=charleskenaprose/><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/kena-upanishad00xxxxuoft#page/23/mode/2up Kena Upanishad] Mantra 12, G Prasadji (Translator), pages 23–26</ref> Indra shares this knowledge with Agni and Vayu. The ''Kena Upanishad'' closes these sections by stating that "Agni, Vāyu and Indra" are revered first because they were the first among gods to realize Brahman.<ref name=pauldeussen34>{{cite book |first=Paul |last=Deussen |title=Sixty Upaniṣads of the Veda, Part 1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8mSpQo9q-tIC |year=1980|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1468-4|pages=207–208, 211–213 verses 14–28}}</ref><ref name=charleskenaprose>Charles Johnston, Kena Upanishad in The Mukhya Upanishads: Books of Hidden Wisdom, (1920–1931), The Mukhya Upanishads, Kshetra Books, {{ISBN|978-1-4959-4653-0}} (Reprinted in 2014), [http://www.universaltheosophy.com/pdf-library/Kena%20Upanishad_Johnston.pdf Archive of Kena Upanishad – Part 3 as published in Theosophical Quarterly, pages 229–232]</ref> The allegorical legend, states Paul Deussen, aims to teach that all the Vedic gods and natural phenomenon have their basis in the timeless, universal monistic principle called Brahman.<ref name=pauldeussen34/>

Another ancient major Hindu scripture named ''[[Prashna Upanishad]]'' mentions Agni in its second Prashna (question section).<ref>Max Muller, The Upanishads, Part&nbsp;2, [https://archive.org/stream/upanishads02ml#page/274/mode/2up Prasna Upanishad, Second Question Verse 2.1], Oxford University Press, pages 274–275</ref> The section states that Agni and other deities manifest as five gross constituents that combine to make the entire universe, and that all the deities are internalized in the temple of a living body with Agni as the eyes.<ref>{{cite book |first=Paul |last=Deussen |year=1990 |title=Sixty Upaniṣads of the Veda |volume=Part&nbsp;2 |pages=592–593 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0430-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ghISwAACAAJ}}</ref><ref>Robert Hume, [https://archive.org/stream/thirteenprincipa028442mbp#page/n401/mode/2up Prasna Upanishad], Thirteen Principal Upanishads, Oxford University Press, pages 381–382</ref>

Agni is mentioned in many minor Upanishads, such as the ''[[Pranagnihotra Upanishad]]'', the ''[[Yogatattva Upanishad]]'', the ''[[Yogashikha Upanishad]]'', the ''[[Trishikhibrahmana Upanishad]]'' and others.<ref>{{cite book|last= Ayyangar |first=TR Srinivasa |title=The Yoga Upanishads |url=https://archive.org/stream/TheYogaUpanishads/TheYogaUpanisadsSanskritEngish1938#page/n345/mode/2up |year=1938 |publisher=The Adyar Library |pages=92, 314, 355, 378}}</ref> The syncretic and monistic Shaivism text, namely ''[[Rudrahridaya Upanishad]]'' states that Rudra is same as Agni, and Uma is same as Svaha.<ref>{{cite book| last=Ayyangar| first = TRS| year=1953| title=Saiva Upanisads| publisher = Jain Publishing Co. (Reprint 2007)|isbn= 978-0-89581-981-9|page=196}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanskritdocuments.org/doc_upanishhat/rudrahridaya.pdf |title= रुद्रहृदयोपनिषत् (Rudrahridaya Upanishad)|access-date=2 March 2016| language = sa|last= Hattangadi| first= Sunder| year= 2000 | page = 2}}</ref>

[[Mundaka Upanishad]] (2.4) mentioned the seven tongues of Agni as ''kālī'', ''karālī'', ''manojavā'', ''sulohita'', ''sudhāmravarṇā'', ''sphuliṅginī'' and ''visvarucī''.<ref name="Bose1998p55">{{cite book|url=http://www.telugubhakti.com/telugupages/Upanishads/Upanishads/Mundakopanishad.pdf|title=Mundaka Upanishad}}</ref>

==Significance==
Vedic rituals involve Agni. He is a part of many Hindu rites-of-passage ceremonies such as celebrating a birth (lighting a lamp), prayers (aarti lamp), at weddings (the yajna where the bride and groom circle the fire seven times) and at death (cremation). According to ''[[Atharvaveda]]'', it is Agni that conveys the soul of the dead from the pyre to be reborn in the next world or life.<ref name=williams49/> However, this role was in post-Vedic texts subsumed in the role of god Yama.<ref name=williams49/> Agni has been important in temple architecture, is typically present in the southeast corner of a [[Hindu temple]].

[[File:(A) Hindu wedding, Saptapadi ritual before Agni Yajna.jpg|thumb|Saptapadi, a [[Hindu wedding]] ritual, around Agni in progress.]]

===Rites of passage: Hindu wedding===
{{Main|Hindu wedding}}
The most important ritual of Hindu weddings is performed around Agni. It is called the ''Saptapadi'' (Sanskrit for "seven steps/feet") or Sat Phere, and it represents the legal part of Hindu marriage.<ref name=bbc2009>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/hinduism/ritesrituals/weddings.shtml BBC News article on Hinduism & Weddings], Nawal Prinja (24 August 2009)</ref><ref>Office of the Registrar General, Government of India (1962), v. 20, pt. 6, no. 2, Manager of Publications, Government of India, On Hindu wedding rituals</ref> The ritual involves a couple completing seven actual or symbolic circuits around the ''Agni'', which is considered a witness to the vows they make to each other.{{efn|The two rake the holy vow in the presence of Agni&nbsp;... In the first four rounds, the bride leads and the groom follows, and in the final three, the groom leads and the bride follows. While walking around the fire, the bride places her right palm on the groom's right palm and the bride's brother pours some unhusked rice or barley into their hands and they offer it to the fire&nbsp;...<ref name="sinha2008">{{cite book |first=Shivendra Kumar |last=Sinha |year=2008 |title=Basics of Hinduism |isbn=978-81-7806-155-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pSOEETzRVqsC}}</ref>}} Each circuit of the consecrated fire is led by either the bride or the groom, varying by community and region. With each circuit, the couple makes a specific vow to establish some aspect of a happy relationship and household for each other, with Agni as the divine witness to those mutual vows.<ref name="goi1962">{{cite report |title=Census of India, 1961 |year=1962 |volume=20, part&nbsp;6 |number=2 |publisher=Office of the Registrar General, Government of India |department=Manager of Publications, Government of India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0sbUAAAAMAAJ |quote=The bride leads in all the first six pheras but follows the bridegroom on the seventh}}</ref> In Central India and [[Suriname]], the bride leads the first three or four circuits.<ref name="sinha2008"/>

===Rituals: Agnihotra===
{{Main|Agnihotra|Yajna| Śrauta}}

The ''Agnihotra'' involves fire, and the term refers to the ritual of keeping fire at home, and in some cases making "sacrificial offerings" such as milk and seeds to this fire.<ref>{{cite book |first=H.W. |last=Bodewitz |title=The Daily Evening and Morning Offering: (Agnihotra) According to the "Brāhmaṇas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B3e4E4dqZH0C|year=1976|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=978-90-04-04532-3|pages=1–4}}</ref> The [[Srauta]] texts state that it is the duty of man to perform ''Agnihotra''. A wide range of Agnihotra procedures are found in the [[Brahmana]] layer of the Vedas, ranging from the most common simple keeping of sacred fire and its symbolism, to more complicated procedures for the expiation of guilt, to rituals claimed to grant immortality to the performer.<ref>{{cite book |first=H.W. |last=Bodewitz |title=The Daily Evening and Morning Offering: (Agnihotra) According to the "Brāhmaṇas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B3e4E4dqZH0C|year=1976|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=978-90-04-04532-3|pages=5–14}}</ref> According to the ''Jaiminiya Brahmana'', for example, an ''Agnihotra'' sacrifice frees the performer from evil and death.<ref name="Essays">{{cite book|title=Essays in Indian Philosophy, Religion and Literature|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|pages=54, 55|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=b2qPLswTCSIC&pg=PA55 |isbn=9788120819788|year=2004}}</ref> In contrast, states the Shatapatha Brahmana, ''Agnihotra'' is a symbolic reminder and equivalent to the Sun, where the fire keeper is reminded of the heat that creates life, the fire in beings, the heat in the womb behind the cycle of life.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Satapatha-Brahmana|pages=327–329|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=aNE2AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA327 |last1=Eggeling|first1=Julius|year=1882}}</ref>

===Festivals: Holi and Diwali===
{{Main|Holi|Diwali}}
[[File:Holika dahan.jpg|thumb|upright|Agni is a part of the ritual grammar in many Hindu festivals. Above Holika for [[Holi]], includes Agni.<ref name=fowlerholi/>]]
Two major festivals in Hinduism, namely Holi (festival of colors) and Diwali (festival of lights) incorporate Agni in their ritual grammar, as a symbol of divine energy.<ref>{{cite book |first=Elizabeth |last=Peirce |title=Multi-Faith Activity Assemblies |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w0yBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA239 |year=2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-41163-4|pages=238–239}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Stephen P. |last=Huyler |year=2002 |title=Meeting God: Elements of Hindu Devotion |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cnNcDn36VHcC |publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-08905-9|pages=60–64}}</ref> During the autumn celebrations of Diwali, traditional small fire lamps called ''Diya'' are included to mark the festivities. For Holi, Hindus burn bonfires as Holika, on the night before the spring festival. The bonfire marks god Agni, and in rural India mothers carry their babies around the fire clockwise on Holika in Agni's remembrance.<ref name=fowlerholi>{{cite book |first=Jeaneane D. |last=Fowler |year=1997 |title=Hinduism: Beliefs and Practices |page=71 |publisher=Sussex Academic Press|isbn=978-1-898723-60-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RmGKHu20hA0C&pg=PA71}}</ref>

===Forms===
Agni has two forms: ''[[Jataveda]]'' and ''Kravyada'':
* ''Jātaveda'' is the fire that carries the quid-pro-quo offerings to the gods, in which case Agni is light identified with knowledge and with Brahman. In the ''[[Jātaveda]]'' form, "He who knows all creatures", Agni acts as the divine model for the priest. He is the messenger who carries the oblation from humans to the gods, bringing the Gods to sacrifice, and intercedes between gods and humans (Rig Veda I.26.3). Together with Indra and [[Soma (deity)|Soma]], Agni is invoked in the Rig Veda more than any other gods.<ref>Doniger, Wendy (2010). ''The Hindus: An Alternative History''. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-19-959334-7}} (Pbk)</ref>
* ''Kravyād'' (क्रव्याद) is the form of Agni which cremates corpses, the fire of the funeral pyre that triggers the recycling of matter and spirit.<ref>{{cite book |first=Danielle |last=Feller |year=2004 |title=Sanskrit Epics |page=91 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=9788120820081 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G3yQJU-4mOoC&pg=PA91}}</ref> In this way, states Shatapatha Brahmana in verse 2.2.4.8, after one's death and at the time of cremation, Agni heats up and burns only the body, yet by its heat, one is reborn.<ref>{{cite book |first=Walter O. |last=Kaelber |year=1989 |title=Tapta Marga: Asceticism and Initiation in Vedic India |pages=36, 37, 52 |publisher=State University of New York Press |isbn=9780887068133 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JctmC87IhUgC&pg=PA37}}</ref>

===Symbolism===
Agni is symbolism for psychological and physiological aspects of life, states Maha Purana{{Clarify|date=November 2021|reason=There is no clarification of what this Maha purana is. Maha purana can be a hindu text but also a Jainist text.}} section LXVII.202–203. There are three kinds of Agni inside every human being, states this text, the ''krodha-agni'' or "fire of anger", the ''kama-agni'' or "fire of passion and desire", and the ''udara-agni'' or "fire of digestion". These respectively need introspective and voluntary offerings of forgiveness, detachment and fasting, if one desires spiritual freedom and liberation.<ref name=bettina225/>

Agni variously denotes the natural element fire, the supernatural deity symbolized by fire and the inner natural will aspiring for the highest knowledge.<ref>{{cite book |first=John A. |last=Grimes |year=1996 |title=A Concise Dictionary of Indian Philosophy |page=18 |publisher=SUNY Press |isbn=9780791430675 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qcoUFYOX0bEC&pg=PA18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Categorisation in Indian Philosophy|publisher=Ashgate Publishing|page=14|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=zsIMAAAAIAAJ |year=1980}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Bina |last=Gupta |date=19 April 2012 |title=An Introduction to Indian Philosophy |pages=22, 24 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781136653100 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-WepAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA22}}</ref>

Heat, combustion and energy is the realm of Agni which symbolizes the transformation of the gross to the subtle; Agni is the life-giving energy.<ref>{{cite book |first=Jeaneane D. |last=Fowler |year=2012 |title=Hinduism: Beliefs and Practices |page=98 |publisher=Sussex Academic Press |isbn=9781105817267 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IbJ0BQAAQBAJ&pg=PA100}}</ref> ''Agnibija'' is the consciousness of ''tapas'' (proto-cosmic energy); ''agni'' (the energizing principle); the sun, representing the Reality (Brahman) and the Truth (Satya), is ''[[Rta]]'', the order, the organizing principle of everything that is.<ref>{{cite book |editor-first=Kishor |editor-last=Gandhi |year=2007 |title=The Transition to a Global Consciousness |page=294 |publisher=Allied Publishers |isbn=9788184241945 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fYANXQFQcccC&pg=PA294}}</ref>

Agni, who is addressed as ''Atithi'' ('guest'), is also called ''Jatavedasam'' (जातवेदसम्), meaning "the one who knows all things that are born, created or produced".{{refn|Rig Veda I.xliv.4}} He symbolizes will-power united with wisdom.<ref>{{cite book |first=R.L. |last=Kashyap |title=Agni in Rig Veda |page=14 |publisher=Sri Aurobindo Kapali Sastry Institute of Vedic Culture |id={{ASIN|817994042X|country=in}}}}</ref>

Agni is the essence of the knowledge of Existence. Agni destroys ignorance and all delusions, removes nescience. The Kanvasatpathabrahmanam (SB.IV.i.iv.11) calls Agni "wisdom" (मेधायैमनसेऽग्नये स्वाहेति).<ref>{{cite book|title=Kanvasatpathabrahmanam Vol.3|publisher=Motilal Banarsidas|page=21|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=rEpF0GY-vn0C&pg=PA21 |isbn=9788120815490|year=1994}}</ref> Agni is symbolism for "the mind swiftest among (all) those that fly".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Rig Veda|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=783|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fgzVAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA783 |isbn=9780199720781|date=23 April 2014}}</ref>

==Iconography==
{{multiple image
| align = right
| image1 = Agni_god_of_fire.jpg
| width1 = 125
| alt1 = 
| caption1 = 
| image2 = Agni and consort.jpg
| width2 = 116
| alt2 = 
| caption2 = 
| footer = The icons for Agni show wide regional variations. Left: Agni on ram, Right: Agni with goddess Svaha.
}}

The iconography of Agni varies by region.<ref>{{cite book |first=Roshen |last=Dalal |year=2010 |title=Hinduism: An Alphabetical Guide |page=10 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=978-0-14-341421-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DH0vmD8ghdMC&pg=PA10}}</ref> The design guidelines and specifications of his iconography are described in the Hindu [[Agama (Hinduism)|Agama]] texts. He is shown with one to three heads, two to four arms, is typically red-complexioned or smoky-grey complexioned standing next to or riding a ram, with a characteristic dramatic halo of flames leaping upwards from his crown.<ref>{{cite book |first=Anna Libera |last=Dallapiccola |year=2010 |title=South Indian Paintings: A catalogue of the British Museum collection |page=145 |publisher=British Museum Press |isbn=978-0-7141-2424-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L4lHAQAAIAAJ}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The compendium on Gaṇeśa |first=Saligrama Krishna Ramachandra |last=Rao |year=2005 |page=5}}</ref> He is shown as a strong looking man, sometimes bearded, with a large belly because he eats everything offered into his flames, with golden brown hair, eyes and mustache to match the color of fire.<ref name="Daniélou1991p88"/>

Agni holds a rosary in one hand to symbolize his prayer-related role, and a sphere in another hand in eastern states of India. In other regions, his four arms hold an ax, torch, spoon (or fan) and a flaming spear (or rosary).<ref name="Daniélou1991p88">{{cite book |first=Alain |last=Daniélou |year=1991 |title=The Myths and Gods of India: The Classic Work on Hindu Polytheism from the Princeton Bollingen Series |pages=88–89 |publisher=Inner Traditions |isbn=978-0-89281-354-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1HMXN9h6WX0C}}</ref>

Seven rays of light or flames emit from his body. One of his names is ''Saptajihva'', "the one having seven tongues", to symbolize how rapidly he consumes sacrificial butter.<ref name=Jansen>{{cite book |last=Jansen |first=Eva Rudy |year=1993 |title=The Book of Hindu Imagery: Gods, Manifestations and Their Meaning |page=64}}</ref> Occasionally, Agni iconography is shown in ''Rohitasva'' form, which has no ram as his vahana, but where he is pulled in a chariot with seven red horses, and the symbolic wind that makes fire move as the wheels of the chariot.<ref name="Daniélou1991p88"/> In [[Khmer people|Khmer]] art, Agni has been depicted with a rhinoceros as his vahana.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Poole |first1=Colin M. |last2=Duckworth |first2=John W. |year=2005 |title=A documented 20th&nbsp;century record of Javan Rhinoceros ''Rhinoceros sondaicus'' from Cambodia |journal=Mammalia |volume=69 |issue=3–4 |pages=443–444 |doi=10.1515/mamm.2005.039 |s2cid=85394693}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Heinrich |last=Stönner |year=1925 |title=Erklärung des Nashornreiters auf den Reliefs von Angkor-Vat |journal=Artibus Asiae |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=128–130 |doi=10.2307/3248014 |jstor=3248014}}</ref> The number seven symbolizes his reach in all seven mythical continents in ancient Hindu cosmology or colors of a rainbow in his form as the sun.<ref name="CoulterTurner2013p26">{{cite book |author1=Charles Russell Coulter |author2=Patricia Turner |year=2013 |title=Encyclopedia of Ancient Deities |page=26 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-96390-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sEIngqiKOugC}}</ref>

Agni has three forms, namely fire, lightning, and the Sun, forms sometimes symbolized by giving his icon three heads or three legs. He sometimes is shown wearing a garland of fruits or flowers, symbolic of the offerings made into the fire.<ref name="CoulterTurner2013p26"/>

===History===
[[File:Bhuvanesvar014.jpg|thumb|upright|Agni god in southeast corner of the 11th-century [[Rajarani Temple]] in Bhubaneshwar Odisha. The ram is carved below him.]]
The earliest surviving artwork of Agni have been found at archaeological sites near [[Mathura]] (Uttar Pradesh), and these date from 1st-century BCE.<ref name=quantanilla2007>{{cite book  |first=Sonya Rhie |last=Quantanilla |year=2007 |title=History of Early Stone Sculpture of Mathura |publisher=BRILL |isbn=978-9004155374 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X7Cb8IkZVSMC}}</ref>{{rp|pages=215, 366–367, xix, with caption for Figure 86}} In the collection at Bharat Kalā Bhavan, there is a red sandstone sculpture from around the start of the common era but no later than 1st-century CE, identifiable as Agni shown in the garb of a Brahmin, very much like sage [[Kashyapa]]. In the [[Panchala]] coins of [[Agnimitra]], a deity is always present with a halo of flames. In [[Gupta Empire|Gupta]] sculptures, Agni is found with a halo of flames round the body, the sacred thread across his chest, a beard, pot-bellied and holding in his right hand a ''amrtaghata'' (nectar-pot).<ref name=quantanilla2007/>{{rp|pages=215–216}} Many of these early carvings and early statues show just one head, but elaborate details such as ear-rings made of three fruits, a detailed necklace, a slightly smiling face wearing a crown, and flames engraved into the hairs at the back of Agni's statue.<ref name=quantanilla2007/>{{rp|pages=215}}

The iconographic statues and reliefs of god Agni are typically present in the southeast corners of a Hindu temple. However, in rare temples where Agni is envisioned as a presiding astrological divinity, according to texts such as the ''Samarangana Sutradhara'', he is assigned the northeast corner.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Stella Kramrisch |author2=Raymond Burnier |year=1976 |title=The Hindu Temple |page=33 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0223-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NNcXrBlI9S0C}}</ref>

Agni is historically considered to be present in every grihastha (home), and therein presented in one of three forms – ''gārhapatya'' (for general domestic usage), ''āhavaniya'' (for inviting and welcoming a personage or deity) and ''dakshinagni'' (for fighting against all evil).<ref>{{cite book |first=B.K. |last=Chaturvedi |title=Agni Purana |pages=18, 21 |publisher=Diamond Pocket Books |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pTT72k9avd0C&pg=PA5}}</ref> [[Yāska]] states that his predecessor Sākapuṇi regarded the threefold existence of Agni as being in earth, air and heaven as stated by the Rig Veda, but a Brāhmana considered the third manifestation to be the Sun.

==Mythologies==
[[File:107 Agni, Unknown, 14-15th c (23381231282).jpg|thumb|upright|Agni seated on a ram, 14th–15th century Indonesia.]]
A sage of the [[Rig Veda|Ṛg Veda]] (Sūkta IV.iii.11) states that the Sun became visible when Agni was born.<ref>{{cite book |first=Arthur Anthony |last=MacDonell |year=1995 |title=Vedic Mythology |pages=88–99 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=9788120811133 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b7Meabtj8mcC&pg=PA93}}</ref>

===Epics===
Offended by Agni, [[Bhrigu|Bhṛgu]] had cursed Agni to become the devourer of all things on this earth, but [[Brahma]] modified that curse and made Agni the purifier of all things he touched.<ref>{{cite book |title=Encyclopaedia of the Hindu World |year=1992 |volume=1 |pages=210, 212 |publisher=Concept Publishing |isbn=9788170223740 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w9pmo51lRnYC&pg=PA213}}</ref>

In the "Khāṇḍava-daha Parva" ([[Mahabharata|Mahābhārata]] CCXXV), Agni in disguise approaches [[Krishna]] and [[Arjuna]] seeking sufficient food for gratification of his hunger; and on being asked about the kind of food which would gratify, Agni expressed the desire to consume the forest of Khāṇḍava protected by Indra for the sake of [[Takshaka|Takṣaka]], the chief of the ''[[Naga Kingdom|Nāga]]''s. Aided by Krishna and Arjuna, Agni consumes the ''[[Khandava Forest|Khāṇḍava Forest]]'', which burnt for fifteen days, sparing only Aswasena, Maya, and the four birds called ''sarangakas''; later, as a boon Arjuna got all his weapons from Indra and also the bow, ''[[Gandiva|Gāṇḍīva]]'', from [[Varuna|Varuṇa]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Mahabharata |volume=Book 1 |pages=434–447 |website=Sacred-texts.com |url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m01/m01226.htm }}</ref>

There is the story about King [[Shibi (king)|Shibi]] who was tested by Agni assuming the form of a pigeon and by Indra assuming the form of a hawk; Shibi offered his own flesh to the hawk in exchange of pigeon's life. The pigeon which had sought Shibi's shelter was thus saved by the king's sacrifice.<ref>{{cite book |date=April 2008 |title=Eastern Wisdom |page=200 |publisher=Wilder Publications |isbn=9781604593051 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2n2iVpqlLh8C&pg=PA200}}</ref>

''Agniparīkṣā'' or 'the Fire test' has Agni as the witness. In the Rāmāyaṇa, [[Sita|Sītā]] voluntarily goes through this ordeal to prove her virtue.

===Puranas===
Agni is the eldest son of Brahma. In the [[Vishnu Purana|Viṣṇu Purāṇa]], Agni, called ''Abhimāni'' is said to have sprung from the mouth of the ''Virāt Puruṣa'', the Cosmic Man. In another version, Agni emerged from the ritual fire produced by the wife of Dharma (eternal law) named Vasubhāryā (literally, "daughter of Light").<ref name="Danielou" />

According to the Puranic mythology, Agni married [[Svaha|Svāhā]] (invocation offering) and fathered three sons – Pāvaka (purifier), Pāvamāna (purifying) and Śuchi (purity). From these sons, he has forty-five grandchildren which are symbolic names of different aspects of a fire.<ref name="Danielou">{{cite book |first=Alain |last=Danielou |date=December 1991 |title=The Myths and Gods of India |page=88 |publisher=Inner Traditions |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x9RrAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA88 |isbn=9781594777332}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Dowson |first=John |year=1961 |title=A Classical Dictionary of Hindu Mythology and Religion: Geography, history, and literature |publisher=Kessinger Publishing |isbn=0-7661-7589-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6JB-KOXy5k8C&pg=PA7}}</ref> In some texts, Medhā (intelligence) is Agni's sister.<ref name="Danielou" />

==Relationships==
[[File:Karttikeya and Agni - Circa 1st Century CE - Katra Keshav Dev - ACCN 40-2883 - Government Museum - Mathura 2013-02-23 5717.JPG|thumb|Agni (right) with his son Skanda ([[Karttikeya]]), about 1st-century CE.]]

===Wife and children===
Goddess Svāhā is Agni's wife. Her name is pronounced with offerings such as butter and seeds poured into the fire during ceremonies. However, like many names in Hindu traditions, the name Svāhā embeds symbolic meanings, through its relationship with the Vedic word ''Svadhā'' found in the hymns of the ṚgVeda. Thomas Coburn states that the term ''Svadhā'' refers to "one's own particular nature or inclination", and the secondary sense of "a customary pleasure or enjoyment, a refreshment that nourishes".<ref name=coburn164>{{cite book |first=Thomas B. |last=Coburn |year=1988 |title=Devī-Māhātmya: The Crystallization of the Goddess Tradition |pages=164–165 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-0557-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hy9kf7_TOHgC}}</ref> ''Svāhā'' is also found in the hymns of the Vedic literature, in the sense of "welcome, praise to you". This salutation is a remembrance of Agni, as an aspect of that which is "the source of all beings".<ref name=coburn164/> As a goddess and wife of Agni, Svāhā represents this [[Shakti]].<ref name=coburn166>{{cite book |first=Thomas B. |last=Coburn |year=1988 |title=Devī-Māhātmya: The Crystallization of the Goddess Tradition |pages=165–166, 317–318 with footnotes |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0557-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hy9kf7_TOHgC}}</ref>

In the text ''[[Devi Mahatmya|Devi Māhātmya]]'' of the goddess tradition of Hinduism ([[Shaktism]]), and in the Hindu mythologies, Svāhā is the daughter of [[Daksha]], Svāhā has a crush for Agni. She seduces him by successively impersonating six of seven women at a ''gurukul'' (school) that Agni desired for, and thus with him has a baby who grows to become god [[Kartikeya|Skanda]] – the god of war. Other chapters suggest he was the son of the god [[Shiva]].<ref name=coburn166/>

The Mahābhārata also mentions that when Agni was residing at [[Mahishmati]] he fell in love with the daughter of king Nila. In the guise of a Brahmana, he asked for the hand of the princess, but the king refused and was about to punish him. Agni revealed his true form and flamed up in wrath. The frightened king apologized and bestowed his daughter on Agni. In return, Agni promised protection of the city during any invasion.<ref>Mahabharata Sabha Parva Digvijaya Parva Section XXXI</ref>

===Other gods===
Agni is identified with same characteristics, equivalent personality or stated to be identical as many major and minor gods in different layers of the Vedic literature, including Vāyu, Soma, Rudra (Shiva), Varuṇa and Mitra.<ref name=smith219>{{cite journal |first=Frederick M. |last=Smith |year=1985 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/41693607 |title=Names of Agni in the Vedic ritual |journal=Annals of the Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute |volume=66 |number=1/4 |pages=219–221 with footnotes|jstor=41693607 }}</ref><ref name=macdonell95>{{cite book |first=Arthur Anthony |last=MacDonell |year=1898 |title=Vedic Mythology |page=95 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1113-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b7Meabtj8mcC}}</ref> In hymn 2.1 of the ''ṚgVeda'', in successive verses, Agni is identified to be the same as twelve gods and five goddesses.<ref name=macdonell95/>

Some of the gods that Agni is identified with:
* [[Prajapati|Prajāpati]]: The vedic text ''[[Shatapatha Brahmana]]'', in section 6.1.2 describes how and why Prajāpati is the father of Agni, and also the son of Agni, because they both are the image of the one Ātman (Soul, Self) that was, is and will be the true, eternal identity of the universe.<ref>{{cite book |author1=David Shulman |author2=Guy S. Stroumsa |year=2002 |title=Self and Self-Transformations in the History of Religions |pages=24–25 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-534933-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IyTCl3dzVzYC}}</ref> The Prajāpati, cosmic Purusha and Agni are stated to be the same in sections 6.1.1 and 6.2.1 of ''Shatapatha Brahmana''.<ref name="Baumer1988p216"/>
* [[Varuna|Varuṇa]] and [[Mitra (Vedic)|Mitra]]: when Agni is born, he is Varuṇa; when he is kindled, he is Mitra.<ref name=macdonell95/> He is also stated to become Varuṇa in the evening, and he is Mitra when he rises in the morning.<ref name=macdonell95/>
* Indra: Agni is generally presented as Indra's twin, they both go and appear together.<ref>{{cite book |first=Friedrich Max |last=Müller |year=1897 |title=Contributions to the Science of Mythology |page=[https://archive.org/details/contributionsto01mlgoog/page/n417 827] |publisher=Longmans Green |url=https://archive.org/details/contributionsto01mlgoog}}</ref> In chapter 13.3 of the Atharvaveda, Agni is said to become Indra when he illumines the sky.<ref name=macdonell95/> Agni is also called ''Vishva-Vedāh'',{{efn|विश्ववेदा, appearing in the [[Taittiriya Samhita]] (IV.iii.2.10) – अभून्मम सुमतौ विश्ववेदा आष्ट प्रतिष्ठामविदद्धि गाधम्, and in the [[Rig Veda]]:<br>* ये पायवो मामतेयं ते अग्ने पश्यन्तो अन्धं दुरितादरक्षन् | ररक्ष तान्त्सुक्रितो विश्ववेदा दिप्सन्त इन्द्रपवो नाह देभुः || (R.V. I.147.3)<br>* इन्द्रः सुत्रामा स्ववाँ अवोभिः सुमृळीको भवतु विश्ववेदाः | बाधतां द्वेषो अभयं कृणोतु सुवीर्यस्य पतयः स्याम || (R.V. VI.47.12)}} "dawn," which refers both to Indra, the Protector, and to the all-knowing Agni.<ref>{{cite book  |first=Bal Gangadhar |last=Tilak |date=May 2011 |title=The Arctic Home of the Vedas  |publisher=Arktos |pages=88–93 |isbn=9781907166341 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9TgsNBHYFYYC&pg=PA92}}</ref>
* Rudra: in the [[Rig Veda|ṚgVeda]] Agni is addressed as having the same fierce nature as [[Rudra]].{{refn|According to ''Śatarudriya'' (oblation) section of the [[Yajurveda]]}}{{efn|In a prayer (R.V.I.27.10) addressed to Agni, the sage prays ": जराबोध तद्विविड्ढि विशेविशे यज्ञियाय | स्तोमं रुद्राय दृशिकम् ||," addressing Agni as having the fierce nature of Rudra, the one who makes the evil persons weep.}} The [[Lingam|Shiva-linga]] represents that pillar of fire which is Agni,<ref>{{cite book |first=Devdutt |last=Pattanaik |year=2011 |title=7 Secrets of Shiva |pages=11–13 |publisher=Westland |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IMF2Oagd6KEC |isbn=9789380658636}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stone statue of Shiva as Lingodbhava |publisher=British Museum |url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/asia/s/stone_statue_of_shiva_as_lingo.aspx |access-date=22 July 2016 |archive-date=6 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706053323/http://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/asia/s/stone_statue_of_shiva_as_lingo.aspx |url-status=dead }}</ref> a ''Skambha'' symbolism borrowed in some Buddhist artworks.<ref>{{cite book |first=Umakant Premanand |last=Shah |year=1987 |title=Jaina Iconography |page=11 |publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=978-81-7017-208-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m_y_P4duSXsC}}</ref> The verses 8 through 18 in section 6.1.3 of the ''Shatapatha Brahmana'' state Rudra is same as Agni, who is known by many other names.<ref name="Srinivasan1997p78"/> Later, in section 9.1.1, the Shatapatha Brahmana states, "this entire Agni (fire altar) has now been completed, he is now this god Rudra".<ref name="Srinivasan1997p78">{{cite book |first=Doris |last=Srinivasan |year=1997 |title=Many Heads, Arms, and Eyes: Origin, meaning, and form of multiplicity in Indian art |pages=78–79 |publisher=BRILL Academic |isbn=978-90-04-10758-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vZheP9dIX9wC&pg=PA79}}</ref>
* [[Savitr]] (Sun): Agni is same as Savitr during the day, as he traverses the space delivering light and energy to all living beings.<ref name=macdonell95/>
* Vāyu and Soma: in the [[Vedas]], Agni or 'fire' (light and heat), Vāyu or 'air' (energy and action), and Soma or 'water', are major deities who cooperate to empower all life. In some passages, they are stated to be aspects of the same energy and principle that transforms.<ref name=smith219/><ref>{{cite book |first=Anna J. |last=Bonshek |year=2001 |title=Mirror of Consciousness |page=135 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=9788120817746 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sT13ws7RKgYC&pg=PA135}}</ref>
* [[Gayatri|Gāyatrī]]: is identified with Agni in ''Aitareya Brahmana'' section 1.1, ''Jaiminiya Brahmana'' section 3.184 and ''Taittiriya Brahmana'' section 7.8, and the most revered Gayatri meter in the [[Sanskrit prosody]] and Hindu traditions is associated with Agni.<ref name="Baumer1988p216">{{cite book |author1=Bettina Bäumer |author2=Kapila Vatsyayan |year=1988 |title=Kalatattvakosa: A lexicon of fundamental concepts of the Indian arts |page=216 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1402-8  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uPoIZaGGtiMC&pg=PA216}}</ref>
* [[Vāc]] (goddess of speech) and ''Prāṇa'' (life force): are identified with Agni in ''Jaiminiya Brahmana'' sections 1.1 and 2.54, ''Shatapatha Brahmana'' sections 2.2.2 and 3.2.2.<ref name="Baumer1988p216"/>
* Sarama: in a hymn in praise of Agni,{{efn|स्वाध्यो दिव आ सप्त यह्वी रायो (Rig Veda I.72.8)}} Rishi Parāśara Śāktya speaks of Saramā, the goddess of Intuition, the forerunner of the dawn of Truth in the Human mind, who finds the Truth which is lost.{{efn|He says – विदद् गव्यं सरमा दृहमूर्वमं येना नु कं मानुषी भोजते विट् – "Saramā discovered the strong and wide places of the hidden knowledge; this discovery brings happiness to all human beings".}} It is Saramā who is a power of the Truth, whose cows are the rays of the dawn of illumination and who awakens man who finds Agni standing in the supreme seat and goal.<ref>{{cite book |first=Sri |last=Aurobindo |year=2003 |title=The Secret of the Veda |page=218 |publisher=Sri Aurobindo Ashram Publication |isbn=9788170587149 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fTJb_Y1Tp94C&pg=PA218}}</ref>

==Buddhism==
===Canonical texts===
{{multiple image
| align = right
| image1 = God of Fire, Agni, of the Medicine Buddha Mandala - Google Art Project.jpg
| total_width= 300
| alt1 = 
| caption1 = 
| image2 = Hanabusa Katen, the Fire Deity.jpg
| alt2 = 
| caption2 = 
| footer = '''Left:''' Agni sitting on a red goat, as medicine Buddha in 15th-century Tibetan Buddhist art;<br>'''Right:''' Four-armed Katen (火天) in 17th-century Japan.
}}
''Agni'' (Sanskrit; Pali; ''Aggi'') appears in many Buddhist canonical texts, as both a god as well as a metaphor for the element of heart or fire. In Pali literature, he is also called ''Aggi-Bhagavā'', ''Jātaveda'', and ''Vessānara.''<ref>{{cite web |title=Buddhist Dictionary of Pali Proper Names |website=Tipitaka, Dreikorb, der Palikanon des Theravada Buddhismus |url=http://www.palikanon.com/english/pali_names/dic_idx.html |access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref>

The ''[[Aggi-Vacchagotta Sutta]]'', presents a philosophical exchange between Buddha and a wandering ascetic named ''Śreṇika Vatsagotra'' (Sanskrit; Pali: Senika Vacchagotta).<ref name=buswelllopez852/><ref name="Conze1985p12">{{cite book |first=Edward |last=Conze |year=1985 |title=The Large Sutra on Perfect Wisdom: With the Divisions of the Abhisamayalankara |pages=12–13, 101–102 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-05321-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKTmmaScCGcC&pg=PA678}}</ref> The conversation between Buddha and Śreṇika have remained a part of a debate that continues in modern Buddhism.<ref name=buswelllopez852/><ref>{{cite book |first=Damien |last=Keown |year=2006 |title=Buddhist Studies from India to America: Essays in Honor of Charles S. Prebish |page=19 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-134-19632-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mH2HBJXnFD0C&pg=PA19}}</ref> It is called the Śreṇika heresy ([[Traditional Chinese characters|Traditional Chinese]]: 先尼外道; [[Pinyin]]: Xiānní wàidào; [[Romanization of Japanese|Romaji]]: ''Sennigedō'' 先尼外道).<ref name=buswelllopez852/><ref>{{cite book |first=Peter |last=Harvey |year=2013 |title=An Introduction to Buddhism: Teachings, history, and practices |pages=231–233 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-85942-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u0sg9LV_rEgC}}</ref>

Śreṇika suggested that there is an eternal Self (Atman) that lives in a temporary physical body and is involved in rebirth. In the Buddhist traditions, the Buddha taught there is rebirth and [[Anatta|Anātman]], or that there is no eternal Self. The Pali texts state that Śreṇika disagreed and asked the Buddha many questions, which the Buddha refused to answer, calling his questions as indeterminate. The Buddha clarified that were he to answer Śreṇika's questions, it would "entangle" him.<ref name=buswelllopez852/> The Buddha explains the Dharma with Agni as a metaphor, stating that just like fire is extinguished and no longer exists after it is extinguished, in the same way all ''[[skandha]]'' that constitute a human being are extinguished after death. Different versions of this debate appear throughout scripture across traditions, such as the ''[[Mahaparinibbana Sutta|Mahāparinibbāṇa Sutta]]'', and the ''[[Mahāprajñāpāramitāupadeśa|Mahāprajñāpāramitōpadeśa]].'' In some versions, Śreṇika offers his own simile of Agni to further his views.<ref name=buswelllopez852/> Scholars such as [[Nagarjuna]] have extensively commented on the Śreṇika heresy.<ref name="Conze1985p12"/>

In a manner similar to the Hindu texts, the Buddhist texts also treat Agni (referred to as the fire element ''Tejas'') as a fundamental material and building block of nature. For example, in section 11.31 of the ''[[Visuddhimagga]]'' as well as the Rūpakaṇḍa section of the ''[[Dhammasangani]]'', Agni and Tejas are credited as that which warms, ages, burns and digests food and life processes.<ref name=bettina225/>

===Art===
Agni is featured prominently in the art of the [[Mahayana]] tradition.

In Tibet, he is one of the fifty-one Buddhist deities found in the mandala of [[Bhaisajyaguru|medicine Buddha]].<ref name=rubinagni/><ref>{{cite book | author=Eng Soon Teoh | year=2016 | title=Medicinal orchids of Asia | pages=33–49 | publisher=Springer | location=Singapore | isbn=978-3-319-24272-9}}</ref> He appears in Tibetan [[Manjushri| Manjushri's]] mandalas as well, where he is depicted with Brahma and Indra.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Steven Kossak |author2=Jane Casey Singer |author3=Robert Bruce-Gardner |year=1998 |title=Sacred Visions: Early Paintings from Central Tibet|pages=68–69, 158–159 |publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art |isbn=978-0-87099-862-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lTN6hDziKC0C}}</ref> The Tibetan iconography for Agni strongly resembles that found in the Hindu tradition, with elements such as red-colored skin, a goat vehicle, conical hair and crown, a beard, and wielding a pot of water or fire in one hand, and rosary beads in the other. Such art will often include Buddhist themes such as the dharma wheel, white conch, golden fish, elephant, the endless knot.<ref name=rubinagni>{{cite web |title=Agni, God of Fire, 15th Century Art Work |website=Rubin Museum of Art |url=http://rubinmuseum.org/collection/artwork/agni-god-of-fire}}</ref>

In [[Theravada]] traditions, such as that found in Thailand, Agni is a minor deity. Agni is called ''Phra Phloeng'' (also spelled ''Phra Plerng'', literally, "holy flames").<ref name="Clontz2016p250">{{cite book |first=Jack M. |last=Clontz |year=2016 |title=Khon Mask: Thailand Heritage |page=250 |publisher=MOCA Bangkok |isbn=978-1-78301-872-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VzTFCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA250}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=Justin Thomas McDaniel |author2=Lynn Ransom |year=2015 |title=From Mulberry Leaves to Silk Scrolls: New approaches to the study of Asian manuscript traditions |pages=26–27, 35 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=978-0-8122-4736-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KL-XCgAAQBAJ}}</ref> He is commonly depicted with two faces, eight arms, red in color, wearing a headdress in the shape of a gourd, and emitting flames. Medieval era Thai literature describes him as a deity with seven tongues, a purple crown of smoke, and fiery complexion. He rides a horse chariot, a rhinoceros or a ram.<ref name="Clontz2016p250"/> Phra Phloeng's wife in these texts is stated to be ''Subanee'', ''Garudee'', or ''[[Svaha|Swaha]]''.<ref name="Clontz2016p250"/> Some Thai texts state Nilanon to be their son.<ref>{{cite book |first=Jack M. |last=Clontz  |year=2016 |title=Khon Mask: Thailand Heritage |page=318 |publisher=MOCA Bangkok |isbn=978-1-78301-872-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VzTFCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA250}}</ref>

[[File:Katen.jpg|thumb|The Buddhist Fire God "Katen" (火天) in [[Japanese art]]. Dated 1127 CE, [[Kyoto National Museum]].]]
In East Asian Buddhism, Agni is a [[dharmapāla]] and often classed as one of a group of twelve deities (Japanese: [[:ja:十二天|Jūniten]], 十二天) grouped together as directional guardians.<ref>{{cite web |title=Twelve heavenly deities (devas) |publisher=Nara National Museum |place=Japan |website=emuseum.jp |url=http://www.emuseum.jp/detail/100031/000/000?mode=detail&d_lang=en |access-date=31 December 2015 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304201634/http://www.emuseum.jp/detail/100031/000/000?mode=detail&d_lang=en |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In Japan, he is called "Katen" (火天). He is included with the other eleven devas, which include Taishakuten ([[Śakra (Buddhism)|Śakra/Indra]]), Fūten ([[Vāyu]]), Emmaten ([[Yama]]), Rasetsuten ([[Nirṛti (god)|Nirṛti]]/[[Rakshasa|Rākṣasa]]), Ishanaten ([[Ishana|Īśāna]]), Bishamonten ([[Vaiśravaṇa|Vaiśravaṇa/Kubera]]), Suiten ([[Varuṇa]]) Bonten ([[Brahmā]]), Jiten ([[Pṛthivī]]), Nitten ([[Sūrya|Sūrya/Āditya]]), and Gatten ([[Candra]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Juuniten 十二天 |website=JAANUS |url=http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/j/juuniten.htm |access-date=23 January 2019}}</ref> While iconography varies, he is often depicted as an elderly mountain ascetic with two or three legs, and two or four arms.

==Jainism==

The word Agni in [[Jainism]] refers to fire, but not in the sense of Vedic ideas. Agni appears in Jain thought, as a guardian deity and in its cosmology. He is one of the eight ''dikpalas'', or directional guardian deities in Jain temples, along with these seven: Indra, Yama, Nirrti, Varuna, Vayu, Kubera and Isana. They are typically standing, with their iconography is similar to those found in Hindu and Buddhist temple pantheon.<ref>{{cite book |first=Sehdev |last=Kumar |year=2001 |title=A Thousand Petalled Lotus: Jain Temples of Rajasthan : Architecture & Iconography |page=18 |publisher=Abhinav Publications |isbn=978-81-7017-348-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nSDACkmA_ukC&pg=PA18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=Charles Russell Coulter |author2=Patricia Turner |year=2013 |title=Encyclopedia of Ancient Deities |page=152 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-96390-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sEIngqiKOugC}}</ref><ref>For Osian Jain temple example: {{cite book |first=Asha |last=Kalia |year=1982 |title=Art of Osian Temples: Socio-economic and Religious Life in India, 8th-12th Centuries A.D. |pages=130–131 |publisher=Abhinav Publications |isbn=978-0-391-02558-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3n-sycLo3XQC}}</ref>

In ancient Jain thought, living beings have souls and exist in myriad of realms, and within the earth realm shared by human beings, there are two kinds of beings: mobile and immobile.<ref name=cortfire21/><ref>{{cite book |author1=Neil Dalal |author2=Chloë Taylor |year=2014 |title=Asian Perspectives on Animal Ethics: Rethinking the Nonhuman |page=40 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-317-74995-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AQ5gAwAAQBAJ}}</ref> The mobile beings – which includes tiny insects, birds, aquatic life, animals and human beings – have two or more senses, while the immobile beings have only a single sense (''ekenderiya'').<ref name=bettina225/><ref>{{cite book |first=Christopher Key |last=Chapple |year=2006 |title=Jainism and Ecology: Nonviolence in the Web of Life |pages=xiv–xviii, 3–8 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-2045-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=abLZNdYxay8C&pg=PA56}}</ref> Among the single sense beings are plant beings, air beings (whirlwind{{efn|For other examples from ''Uttaradhyayana Sutra'' text of Jainism, see Chapple.<ref>{{cite book |first=Christopher Key |last=Chapple |year=2006 |title=Jainism and Ecology: Nonviolence in the Web of Life |page=56 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-2045-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=abLZNdYxay8C&pg=PA56}}</ref>}}), earth beings (clay), water beings (dew drop) and fire beings (burning coal, meteor, lightning). The last class of beings are Agni-bodies, and these are believed to contain soul and fire-bodied beings.<ref name="Christopher 2006"/><ref name=cortfire21>{{cite book |first=John E. |last=Cort |year=2001 |title=Jains in the World: Religious values and ideology in India |pages=20–21 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-803037-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PZk-4HOMzsoC}}</ref> [[Ahimsa]], or non-violence, is the highest precept in Jainism. In their spiritual pursuits, Jain monks go to great lengths to practice Ahimsa; they neither start Agni nor extinguish Agni because doing so is considered violent to "fire beings" and an act that creates harmful [[Karma]].<ref name=bettina225/><ref>{{cite book |first=Christopher Key |last=Chapple |year=2006 |title=Jainism and Ecology: Nonviolence in the Web of Life|pages=46, 31–48 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-2045-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=abLZNdYxay8C&pg=PA56}}</ref>

''Agni-kumara'' or "fire princes" are a part of Jain theory of rebirth and a class of reincarnated beings.<ref name="Helmuth 1999"/> Agni or Tejas are terms used to describe substances and concepts that create beings, and in which transmigrating soul gets bound according to Jainism theology.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Bettina Bäumer |author2=Kapila Vatsyayan |year=1988 |title=Kalatattvakosa: A Lexicon of Fundamental Concepts of the Indian Arts |pages=271–274 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1402-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uPoIZaGGtiMC}}</ref>

==Ancient medicine and food==
{{main article|Agni (Ayurveda)}}
Agni, as constitutive principle of fire or heat, was incorporated in Hindu texts of ancient medicine such as the ''[[Charaka Samhita]]'' and ''[[Sushruta Samhita]]''. It is, along with Soma, the two classification premises in the pre-4th century CE medical texts found in Hinduism and Buddhism. Agni-related category, states Dominik Wujastyk, included that of "hot, fiery, dry or parched" types, while Soma-related category included "moist, nourishing, soothing and cooling" types. This classification system was a basis of grouping medicinal herbs, seasons of the year, tastes and foods, empirical diagnosis of human illnesses, veterinary medicine, and many other aspects of health and lifestyle.<ref>{{cite journal |first=D. |last=Wujastyk |year=2004 |title= Agni and Soma: A Universal Classification|journal= Studia Asiatica (Bucharest, Romania)|volume=4–5 |pages=347–369 |pmid=19030111 |pmc=2585368 |doi=<!-- --> }};<br>{{cite book |first=D. |last=Wujastyk |year=2003 |title=The Roots of Ayurveda: Selections from Sanskrit Medical Writings |pages=xviii, 74, 197–198 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-14-044824-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TaZCwjtmzZYC}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Chopra |first1=Arvind |last2=Doiphode |first2=Vijay V. |year=2002 |title=Ayurvedic medicine: core concept, therapeutic principles, and current relevance |journal=[[Medical Clinics of North America]] |volume=86 |issue=1 |pages=75–89 |doi=10.1016/s0025-7125(03)00073-7 |pmid=11795092}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Loukas | first1=Marios | last2=Lanteri | first2=Alexis | last3=Ferrauiola|display-authors=et al | first3=Julie | title=Anatomy in ancient India: a focus on the Susruta Samhita | journal=Journal of Anatomy | volume=217 | issue=6 | year=2010 | pages=646–650 | doi=10.1111/j.1469-7580.2010.01294.x | pmid=20887391 | pmc=3039177}}</ref>

Agni was viewed as the life force in a healthy body, the power to digest foods, and innate in food.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Zimmermann | first=Francis | title=The jungle and the aroma of meats: An ecological theme in Hindu medicine | journal=Social Science & Medicine | volume=27 | issue=3 | year=1988 | pages=197–206 | doi=10.1016/0277-9536(88)90121-9 | pmid=3175704 | pmc=1036075 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last=Guha | first=Amala | title=Ayurvedic Concept of Food and Nutrition | journal=Ayurveda Health and Nutrition| volume=4|number=1| year=2006 | url=http://digitalcommons.uconn.edu/som_articles/25 | access-date=12 October 2016}}</ref> In Ayurveda, states Fleischman, "the amount of Agni determines the state of health".<ref>{{cite journal | last=Fleischman | first=P. R. | title=Ayurveda | journal=International Journal of Social Psychiatry | volume=22 | issue=4 | year=1976 | pages=282–287 | doi=10.1177/002076407602200406 | pmid=799625 | s2cid=220642164 }}</ref>

[[Agni (Ayurveda)|Agni]] is an important entity in [[Ayurveda]]. Agni is the fiery metabolic energy of digestion, allows assimilation of food while ridding the body of waste and toxins, and transforms dense physical matter into subtle forms of energy the body needs. ''Jathar-agni'' determines the production of hydrochloric acid in the stomach, ''Bhuta-agni'' determines the production of bile in the liver, ''Kloma-agni'' determines the production of sugar-digesting pancreatic enzymes and so forth. The nature and quality of these ''agnis'' depend on one's ''dosha'' which can be – ''vata'', ''pitta'' or ''kapha''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Yoga Journal Sep–Oct 2003|publisher=Active Interest Media|page=38|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=u-kDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38 |date= September–October 2003}}</ref>

Agni is also known as ''Vaisvanara''. Just as the illuminating power in the fire is a part of Agni's own effulgence, even so the heating power in the foods digestive and appetizing power is also a part of Agni's energy or potency.<ref>{{cite book |title=Srimadbhagavadagita Tattvavivecani |first=Jayadayal |last=Goyandka |publisher=Gita Press |at=page&nbsp;613, verses BG&nbsp;15.14 |url=http://www.vedicbooks.net/srimad-bhagavad-gita-tattva-vivechani-hindi-p-16541.html }}</ref>

